rming Media -- t17. The Superhero with a Thousand Faces: Visual Narratives on Film and Paper -- t18. "Tonight Your Director Is John Ford": The Strange Journey of Stagecoach from Screen to Radio -- t19. M*A *S*H Notes -- tAfterword: Rethinking Remakes -- tNOTES ON CONTRIBUTORS -- tCREDITS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis title was originally published in 1998.Play It Again, Sam is a timely investigation of a topic that until now has received almost no critical attention in film and cultural studies: the cinematic remake. As cinema enters its second century, more remakes are appearing than ever before, and these writers consider the full range: Hollywood films that have been recycled by Hollywood, such as The Jazz Singer, Cape Fear, and Robin Hood; foreign films including Breathless; and Three Men and a Baby, which Hollywood has reworked for American audiences; and foreign films based on American works, among them Yugoslav director Emir Kusturica's Time of the Gypsies, which is a ";makeover"; of Coppola's Godfather films. As these essays demonstrate, films are remade by other films (Alfred Hitchcock went so far as to remake his own The Man Who Knew Too Much) and by other media as well. The editors and contributors draw upon narrative, film, and cultural theories, and consider gender, genre, and psychological issues, presenting the ";remake"; as a special artistic form of repetition with a difference and as a commercial product aimed at profits in the marketplace. The remake flourishes at the crossroads of the old and the new, the known and the unknown. Play It Again, Sam takes the reader on an eye-opening tour of this hitherto unexplored territory. This title is part of UC Press's Voices Revived program, which commemorates University of California Press’s mission to seek out and cultivate the brightest minds and give them voice, reach, and impact. Drawing on a backlist dating to 1893, Voices Revived makes high-quality, peer-reviewed scholarship accessible once again using print-on-demand technology. This title was originally published in 1998.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFilm remakes. 4acinema. 4afilm analysis. 4afilm history. 4afilm theory. 4afilm. 4ahistory of theatre. 4amedia. 4apresent. 4atheatre. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aAufderheide, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiguenet, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandy, Leo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrashinsky, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEberwein, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbard, Krin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgakas, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenberg, Harvey R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmlund, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorton, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKolker, Robert P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKönigsberg, Ira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougal, Stuart Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDougal, Stuart Y., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato